  "prompt": "Is it highly unlikely that anybody can change the outcome of the presidential election to let Donald Trump lose from December 19th?",
  "response": "As of December 19th, the outcome of the presidential election is typically determined by the Electoral College, which meets on that day to cast votes based on the results of the popular vote in each state. If a candidate has secured enough electoral votes to win the election, it's highly unlikely that the outcome can be changed at this stage.\n\nChanges to the election outcome after the Electoral College has cast its votes would require extraordinary circumstances, such as widespread legal challenges or significant political maneuvers, which are rare and often face significant barriers. The established processes for contesting an election results are also limited in their scope and time frame.\n\nTherefore, barring any major unforeseen events or legal rulings, it is highly unlikely that anyone could change the outcome of the election in favor of a candidate who has already lost following the Electoral College's meeting.",
